(
<figureCitation box="[159,246,997,1023]" captionStart="FIGURES 33–40" captionStartId="61.[151,269,1675,1699]" captionTargetBox="[284,1299,255,1609]" captionTargetId="figure-190@61.[265,1321,194,1653]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 33–40. Adults. 33, Melanchra adjuncta, m, Virginia, Montgomery Co.; 34, Melanchra assimilis, m, Canada, Newfoundland, Doyles, Codroy Valley, 8 July 1959, D.C. Ferguson; 35, Polia detracta, m, North Carolina, Haywood Co., Purchase Knob, 4924 ft., 8 June 2002, J. Adams, USNMENT 00153850; 36, Polia detracta, m, Tennessee, Sevier Co., Campsite 20, 2520 ft., 22 June 2004, M.G. Pogue, USNMENT 00220921; 37, Polia detracta, m, North Carolina, Swain Co., 15.2 mi NE GSMNP ent. on 441, Deep Creek Trail, 4815 ft., 8 June 2003, M.G. Pogue, USNMENT 00155420; 38, Polia imbrifera, m, North Carolina, Haywood Co., Polls Gap, Rough Fork Trail, 5140 ft., 28 June 2004, M.G. Pogue, USNMENT 00221234; 39, Polia nimbosa, m, North Carolina, Swain Co., 5.6 mi SW of Jct. 441 &amp; Clingmans Dome Rd., Noland Divide Trail, 5950 ft., 28 July 2003, M.G. Pogue, USNMENT 00156519; 40, Polia nimbosa, m, Tennessee, Sevier Co., 1.3 mi W of Jct. 441 &amp; Clingmans Dome Rd., Road Prong Trail, 28 July 2003, M.G. Pogue, USN- MENT 00156574." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5312388" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5312388/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
, Map 21)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1072,1322]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,334,1072,1098]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Identification:</emphasis>
Forewing length 
<quantity box="[549,682,1072,1098]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" unit="mm" value="23.5" valueMax="26.0" valueMin="21.0">21–26 mm</quantity>
. Frons has a black horizontal stripe below antennae. The male antenna is serrate and is filiform in the female. This is a large dark gray species with prominent white orbicular and reniform spots that are suffused with gray and bordered by black scales. Claviform spot is gray with a black border. Proximal to the subterminal line are various sized black triangulate spots with the largest an oblong spot just above the tornus. Hindwing is dark gray with a faint postmedial line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1436,1072,1322]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,370,1258,1284]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Flight period:</emphasis>
June to early August and one record from mid-October, apparently double brooded in the Park.
</paragraph>
